 R_1T&=9\Omega  \\ R_2&=1\Omega\\ \text{ We can write,} \\ \frac{V_o(s)}{V_{in}(s)}&=\frac{R_2+\frac{1}{sC}}{R_1+R_2+\frac{1}{sC}}  \\ &=\frac{1+R_2\cdot Cs}{1+(R_1+R_2)Cs}  \\ &=\frac{1+R_2\cdot Cs}{1+\left (\frac{R_1+R_2}{R_2} \right )R_2 Cs}\\ \text{Let,  } R_2C&=T  \\ \frac{R_1+R_2}{R_2}&=\beta \\ \text{Hence, } \\ \frac{V_o(s)}{V_{in}(s)}&=\frac{1+Ts}{(1+\beta Ts)} \\ \text{Which represent }& \text{a lag compensator}\\ \because \text{ Here, } T&=R_2C=1.1=1 sec \\ \beta &=\frac{1+9}{1}=10\\  \text{Maximum phase }& \text{lag occurs at frequency}\\ \omega _n&=\frac{1}{T\sqrt{\beta }} \\ &=\frac{1}{1\sqrt{10}} =0.316 rad/sec.
